The problem is from a semantic error in the nested 'is_prime' function. With the line "if x % i:", you are checking to see if x is divisible by i. In the function's current state, if this check evaluates as False at any point (i.e. x is divisible by i, which is enough to determine that x is not prime), control gets passed back to the beginning of the for loop. This way the function only returns True if x is divisible by every value of i, rather than the other way around - the function should only return True if x is NOT divisible by any value of i. This can be easily fixed by modifying the divisibility test to "if x % i == 0:" or "if not x % 0:" instead. Additionally, to ensure the returned list is truly inclusive of both ends of the given range, you should adjust the range parameters in the return statement of the "prime_numbers_in_range" function to (a, b+1) rather than (a, b).

